# Automated Dependency Vulnerability Scanning for OWASP Juice Shop

# **1\. Objective**

Automate the detection and reporting of dependency vulnerabilities in the OWASP Juice Shop app using GitHub Actions, npm audit, Snyk, Slack notifications, and Pull Request comments with vulnerability summaries.

# **2\. Project Setup**

## **2.1 — Fork OWASP Juice Shop**

1\. Go to https://github.com/juice-shop/juice-shop.  
2\. Click 'Fork' and select your GitHub account.  
3\. Clone your fork locally using vs code:  
   git clone https://github.com/\<your-username\>/\<your-repo\>.git  
   cd \<your-repo\>

## **2.2 — Move Juice Shop into a subdirectory**

mkdir juice\_shop  
mv \* juice\_shop/ 2\>/dev/null || true

Ensure the structure looks like:  
📁 your-repo/  
├── 📁 .github/  
│   └── 📁 workflows/  
│       └── dependency-scan.yml  
└── 📁 juice\_shop/  
    ├── package.json  
    ├── package-lock.json

# **3\. GitHub Actions Setup**

On vs code, create the workflow folder using: mkdir \-p .github/workflows. Then create a new file named **dependency-scan.yml** inside that folder.

# **4\. Configure Secrets**

## **4.1 — Snyk secret**

In order to scan the application’s dependencies with snyk, it needs to authenticate and therefore a token needs to be configured.  Without a secret, the workflow would fail.

To obtain a snyk token, do the following:

* Go to https://app.snyk.io  
* Log in and go to Account Settings → API Token  
* Copy the token.

Go to GitHub → Repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret.  
Add the SNYK\_TOKEN

## **4.2 — Slack webhook url**

To send vulnerability notification to slack channel, do the following:

- Create a Slack Incoming Webhook  
  * Go to your Slack workspace (create an account if you don’t have one): [https://api.slack.com/apps](https://api.slack.com/apps)  
  * Click “Create New App” → “From scratch”.  
  * Give it a descriptive name: Juice Shop Dependency Scan Alerts.  
  * In your app, go to Incoming Webhooks → toggle “Activate Incoming Webhooks”.  
  * Click “Add New Webhook to Workspace” and choose your channel (e.g. \#cyber-consulting-collaboration).  
  * Copy the Webhook URL — it looks like this: https://hooks.slack.com/services/T00000000/B00000000/XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX  
- Store the Webhook securely in GitHub

  * Go to GitHub → Repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret \> SLACK\_WEBHOOK\_URL

  * Paste your Slack webhook URL.

NB:  GITHUB\_TOKEN used as an environment variable in this project is automatically provided by GitHub

# **5\. Workflow YAML Overview**

The workflow integrates npm audit, Snyk scanning, GitHub PR comments, and Slack notifications. It runs automatically on pushes and pull requests to main.

Key steps in the yaml file include:  
1\. Checkout repository  
2\. Setup Node.js  
3\. Install dependencies  
4\. Run npm audit  
5\. Run Snyk scan  
6\. Generate vulnerability summary  
7\. Post results to PR  
8\. Fail on high/critical vulnerabilities  
9\. Send Slack notification on failure

You can find an example dependency yaml file here \- [https://github.com/AdeolaMercy/devsecops\_proj/blob/master/.github/workflows/dependency-check.yml](https://github.com/AdeolaMercy/devsecops_proj/blob/master/.github/workflows/dependency-check.yml)

# **7\. Verification Steps**

1. Create a new branch: git checkout \-b feature/dependency-pipeline 

Add and Push the workflow file:  
   git add .github/workflows/dependency-scan.yml  
   git commit \-m 'Add npm \+ Snyk dependency scan workflow'  
   git push origin feature/dependency-pipeline

2\. Go to GitHub and you will see a PR request. Click compare

3\. Go to GitHub → Actions tab → confirm workflow run.  
4\. Open a Pull Request → check PR comment.  
4\. Check Slack for notifications.  
6\. Review workflow artifacts (npm-audit.json, snyk-report.json).

# **9\. Optional Enhancements**

• Integrate OWASP Dependency-Check for third-layer analysis.  
• Generate and publish HTML reports.  
• Add GitHub Advanced Security (CodeQL).  
• Trigger nightly vulnerability scans via cron schedule.
